<subSubSection id="02C66578FFFEFFBFFF3D9B656D137C58" pageId="19" pageNumber="33" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFEFFBFFF3D9B656B877A18" blockId="19.[151,756,1825,2073]" pageId="19" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFEFFBFFF3D9B6568057A58" bold="true" box="[151,264,1825,1849]" pageId="19" pageNumber="33">Remarks:</emphasis>
It is characterized by an elongate test with a short spine on the initial end and longitudinal costae which extend non-interruptedly across sutures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A6336F3FFFEFFBFFF3D9BC56D137C58" blockId="19.[151,756,1825,2073]" lastBlockId="19.[832,1436,257,313]" pageId="19" pageNumber="33">
<emphasis id="78A8EAE1FFFEFFBFFF3D9BC568DE7AF8" bold="true" box="[151,467,1921,1945]" pageId="19" pageNumber="33">Stratigraphic distribution:</emphasis>
This species is widely recorded in the Cretaceous and Lower Eocene deposits of Europe and America (LE ROY, 1953). In 
<collectingCountry id="32CB7663FFFEFFBFFDE59B866B9C7ABB" box="[591,657,1986,2010]" name="Egypt" pageId="19" pageNumber="33">Egypt</collectingCountry>
, it seems to have a wide range when all records of its occurrence are taken into consideration (SAID &amp; KENAWY, 1956). It is recorded in the Maastrichtian and Paleocene zones of Esh El Mallaha area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
